author: speaker
text:
I'm going through some things with my feelings and myself. I barely sleep and I do nothing but think about how I'm worthless and how I shouldn't be here.
   I've never tried or contemplated suicide. I've always wanted to fix my issues, but I never get around to it.
   How can I change my feeling of being worthless to everyone?

author: listener
text: Hello, and thank you for your question and seeking advice on this.

author: listener
text: Feelings of worthlessness is unfortunately common.

author: listener
text: In fact, most people, if not all, have felt this to some degree at some point in their life.

author: listener
text: You are not alone.

author: listener
text: Changing our feelings is like changing our thoughts - it's hard to do.

author: listener
text: Our minds are so amazing that the minute you change your thought another one can be right there to take it's place.

author: listener
text: Without your permission, another thought can just pop in there.

author: listener
text: The new thought may feel worse than the last one!

author: listener
text: My guess is that you have tried several things to improve this on your own even before reaching out on here.

author: speaker
text: Hello everyone, I love this sub but have never posted and today I feel a need to. One example of this is the other day, my husband went out to lunch with his mom and my son while she was at work. Have a wonderful day.

author: listener
text: You are in a tough situation.

text:

author: listener
text: That is intense.

author: speaker
text:
I'm going through some things with my feelings and myself. I barely sleep and I do nothing but think about how I'm worthless and how I shouldn't be here.
   I've never tried or contemplated suicide. I've always wanted to fix my issues, but I never get around to it.
   How can I change my feeling of being worthless to everyone?

author: listener
text: That is intense.

author: listener
text: Depression is a liar.

author: listener
text: Sometimes depression places these glasses over our eyes, these dark sunglasses that change how we see things.

author: listener
text: Depression tells us things like "you're worthless" "no one likes you" "don't worry about doing anything. "

author: listener
text: And it is so easy for us to listen and to be tricked into thinking that just because we feel something means it is true.

author: listener
text: Please know that even if you are feeling worthless right now, that doesn't mean you are worthless.

author: listener
text: The first step to working through this is recognizing what is going on.

author: listener
text: Recognizing when depression is telling you the same story (ie; being worthless) with different words (ie worthless here, worthless there) and making an effort to talk back.

author: listener
text: While I can not give you a diagnosis of depression, reading what you are going through, it sounds like you might need help to get back on track.

author: listener
text: It must be really difficult to experience what your going through right now.

author: listener
text: It takes a lot of courage to reach out.

author: listener
text: It sounds like you want to get better, but perhaps need some help to get over the hump.

author: speaker
text: So, the other day I was explaining to my friend about the fact I have these moments where I think about something horrible, something that hasn't happened but COULD happen, and it makes me freak out a little, to the point I have to repeat to myself "It didn't happen. Several times before I can be calm. I know I could google this, but human interaction is more informative than reading a webMD.

author: listener
text: Those are Intrusive thoughts.

author: speaker
text: I've been very hesitant to go to a doctor to be diagnosed with something or even get a recommendation to a psychiatrist or something because I'm afraid to talk about me and talk to new people. Or worse yet I feel like I won't be able to keep my composure at the office and just cry uncontrollably there. Sorry for the long rant, I felt like writing this out would help a bit.

author: listener
text: You're definitely not alone in feeling and reflecting the way you describe.

author: listener
text: But if you've got real friends around, they'll want to know.

author: listener
text: I hated having no energi, I cried often, felt useless.

author: listener
text: Talking to someone, a doctor or psychologist, is key to get a hand in learning to deal with emotional issues/traumas/etc.

author: speaker
text: Thanks for your input I really really appreciate it. I have been mulling it over about talking about this with my friends but I'm just stuck and can't even begin to express myself and I'm just anxious about it. I don't want to strain my relationship with them or lose them because I'm not myself anymore. I hate this. I don't want to be like this. I don't know why I'm like this.

author: listener
text: I truly understand what you mean, the fear of them turning you away or not taking you seriously, even losing them due to something you're not entirely in control of.

text:
I'm going through some things with my feelings and myself. I barely sleep and I do nothing but think about how I'm worthless and how I shouldn't be here.
   I've never tried or contemplated suicide. I've always wanted to fix my issues, but I never get around to it.
   How can I change my feeling of being worthless to everyone?

author: listener
text:
You have
several things going on here.

author: listener
text:
The sleep should be addressed with a primary care
physician to rule out any physical issues.

author: listener
text:
Sleep is the big reset and allows us
to function in the day.

author: listener
text:
What happens during a depression is that our thoughts
race and it is as though our “brain won’t shut off.

author: listener
text:
” Medication can help with
this.

author: listener
text:
I also use a Pranayama yoga breathing technique called the four
fold breath which has great usefulness for relaxing us  and often does work quite well with allowing
us to sleep.

author: listener
text:
You can read about it here:    https://billleavitttherapy.com/breathing-techniques-the-four-fold-breath/Your
thoughts on feeling worthless to everyone fall under a heading of thinking
error in Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) known as overgeneralization.

author: listener
text:
In CBT
thoughts lead to emotions, so we are going to pick the statement apart and then
reframe it.

author: listener
text:
First list
the evidence that contradicts the thought.

author: listener
text:
Has anyone in the past made positive
comments toward you?

author: listener
text:
This might be hard to recall if we are in a rut, but at
some point in life we frequently have had some positives expressed towards us
by others.

text: It sounds like you are having some pretty severe depression.

author: listener
text: Depression can cause insomnia, and make a person focus on their own perceptions that they are "worthless".

author: listener
text: It is important to remember that other people may not truly perceive you as worthless.

author: listener

author: listener
text: I think that it is extremely important when you are this depressed, to sit down and write down some positives about yourself.

author: listener
text: What are your strengths?

author: listener
text: What are some positive things that your have done in your life?

author: listener
text: It concerns me that you are having suicidal thoughts.

author: speaker
text:
I have so many issues to address. I have a history of sexual abuse, I’m a breast cancer survivor and I am a lifetime insomniac.    I have a long history of depression and I’m beginning to have anxiety. I have low self esteem but I’ve been happily married for almost 35 years.
   I’ve never had counseling about any of this. Do I have too many issues to address in counseling?

author: listener
text: Absolutely not.

author: listener
text: It sounds like you have significant trauma and it will continue to impact your depression until it is dealt with.

author: speaker
text: A few years ago I was making love to my wife when for no known reason I lost my erection,    Now I'm In my early 30s and my problem has become more and more frequent. This is causing major problems for my ego and it's diminishing my self esteem. This has resulted in ongoing depression and tearing apart my marriage.    I am devastated and cannot find a cause for these issues. I am very attracted to my wife and want to express it in the bedroom like I used to.    What could be causing this, and what can I do about it?

author: listener
text: If you haven't already, please see a doctor.

author: listener
text: ED can be caused by any number of physical conditions and you need to get checked out.

author: listener
text: Once you have ruled out any physical issues that interfere with getting an  erection, it's time to look for more subtle causes.

author: listener
text: Unfortunately, you may have gotten yourself into a mind set of "I hope I can, but what if I can't? "

author: speaker
text: I struggle with depression as well as pretty intense mood swings throughout the month. I experience highs where I feel amazing and energetic and then lows where I lack focus, energy, and generally have a more dark outlook on my life. How can I live a more balanced life?

author: listener
text: Are you certain your highs and lows are directly related to your cycle?

author: listener
text: It's possible that there are at least some contributing factors, even if they are  as a result of hormonal fluctuations.

author: listener
text: For example, at the start of your period, do you have that "I feel great" feeling, or are you tired and down?

author: listener
text: Mid-cycle (assuming your periods are regular), do you find yourself napping or ready to run a race?

author: listener
text: Either way, how you feel may be leading you to behaviors that contribute to your changes in energy and optimism.

author: listener
text: Let's say that the few days before your period, you feel cranky, bloated and want salty food.

author: listener

author: listener
text: So the question becomes, are you trying to fix the feelings on the inside (the internal stuff), with the trappings of all the stuff on the outside (the internal)?

author: speaker
text:
I've never been able to talk with my parents. My parents are in their sixties while I am a teenager. I love both of them but not their personalities. I feel that they do not take me seriously whenever I talk about a serious event in my life. If my dad doesn’t believe me, then my mom goes along with my dad and acts like she doesn’t believe me either. I’m a pansexual, but I can’t trust my own parents.

author: listener
text: Hi there.

author: listener
text: Being 15 years old can be a very difficult time in your teenage life.

author: listener
text: I remember when I was 15 and how I often felt my parents weren’t listening to me.

author: listener
text: It’s even more difficult when you feel that you do not have a friend that you can confide in.

author: listener
text: Having depression in the past and being able to get through it shows me that you can get through anything!

author: listener
text: Depression alone is a very difficult problem to work through.

author: listener
text: In addition to the communication problem with your parents, it appears that you are also struggling with stress and anxiety.

author: listener
text: We all have stress and anxiety in our lives.

author: listener
text: If we didn’t, none of us would be living.

author: listener
text: Anxiety & stress keep us on our toes!

author: listener
text: Often, I have to remind myself of this as well.

author: listener
text: However, it is how we manage stress and anxiety, so it will not overcome our lives.

author: listener
text: Are you familiar with relaxation techniques, such as: deep breathing exercises, meditation or yoga?

author: listener
text: Relaxation Techniques can help you tremendously in reducing your stress and anxiety.

author: listener
text: Deep breathing exercises are helpful when you are on the go, such as school, shopping, out with friends or whatever extracurricular activities you engage in.

author: listener
text: Most people do not take full advantage of their lung capacity.

author: listener
text: I know, that sounds silly.

author: listener
text: But, it’s true.

author: listener
text: You would be surprised how much air you lungs can hold.

author: listener
text: Imagine being in the Doctor’s office and taking deep breaths.

author: listener
text: This is what you want to do when you are feeling overwhelmed and/or stressed.

author: listener
text: Take a moment to take in at least 10 deep breaths and let them out slowly.

author: listener
text: You will be surprised how well you feel afterwards.

author: listener
text: Meditation and Yoga are also healthy forms to working through stress and anxiety.

author: listener
text: You will need a quiet place for your meditation.

author: listener
text: You want to be “in the moment” and take in the peace and serenity.

author: listener
text: All it takes is a quiet place, closing your eyes and thinking of your “happy place.

author: listener
text: ” Some people use meditation music as well.

author: listener
text: If you have access to this type of music and or the internet for more ways to practice meditation, please go for it!

author: listener
text: Yoga on the other hand will take a little more work and practice.

author: listener
text: I would not suggest you learning this on your own, if you have never attempted yoga before.

author: listener
text: Find an experienced Yoga instructor to teach you the ropes and/or ask your school counselor about the possibility of getting someone to come to the school to teach the students.

author: listener
text: Lastly, in regards to your parents it is very important to be able to have a relationship where you feel comfortable communicating.

text: Adults who come from abusive home histories (physical, emotional, or even psychological), may take a long time to heal from that abuse.

author: listener
text: We carry our past with us everywhere we go, and it is up to us to find resolutions to past hurts.

author: listener

author: listener
text: If your husband is changing his mind about whether or not he wants to stay in the relationship, I wonder if you both might benefit from seeing a therapist who specializes in couples.

author: listener
text: In my training working with couples, partners come into counseling with one of three goals in mind: strengthening the relationship, getting a divorce, or making a decision.

author: listener
text: The decision could be whether or not stay together or it could be any number of other things, such as what state to live in.

author: listener
text: When you ask whether you have to respect whatever decision he makes, respecting his decision does not mean that you have to agree with what he decides.

author: speaker
text: I'm in my late 50s. I never loved or have been loved. I need deeper help than is offered in my small town, but I cannot leave this town because of agoraphobia. I find myself losing hope more and more. My brain barely works anymore, and my memory so small, I forget in a moment. I serve no purpose. I'm incapable of work or anything of value, and I never have been. I’m a complete waste of time and resources, and yet I keep trying. Why? Why does God insist that I continue to exist? I’m not suicidal, just tired.

author: listener
text: The fact that you're reaching out says that there is something in you that wants this to be different, and that drive might be something worth tapping into.

author: speaker
text: I have bipolar disorder, paranoid personality disorder, posttraumatic stress disorder, anxiety and obsessive-compulsive disorder. I last self-harmed a week ago. When I am stressed, overwhelmed, hurt, or angry, the urge to self-harm is all I can think of. I am trying to seek help.

author: listener
text: Seeking professional help does not mean that you will necessarily be admitted into an inpatient setting - though  to be honest, that can become an option if you feel unsafe or if you are unable to plan for safety.

author: speaker
text: No one wants to see you like this, no one cares to see you like this, they only like you when you're pretending to smile. But I suffer from social anxiety, and just the thought of meeting people, or talking to people in person turns my stomach. I didn't want those people feeling like I did on the inside. Hell, from what people tell me my emotions are "over dramatic", and "people have had it worse".

author: listener
text: Don't listen to those people that tell you your stories over dramatic.

author: listener
text: Granted I don't open up about some things because I feel like it's me taking things to serious but everyone has pain.

author: listener
text: All of our pain is different but no one can rightfully say "I'm worse off than you".

author: speaker
text: This isn't the first time I've been in the red during college, I dropped a bunch of classes my second year at community college and I failed my first year and was put on Academic probation when I transferred to a university. The next semester would be my fifth college year and my parents are not exactly happy with the prospect that it's taking me five years to graduate college.

author: listener
text: It honestly isn't that uncommon for people to take more than 4 years to graduate anymore.

author: listener
text: As for the login thing, I wouldn't even give your dad your login.

author: listener
text: Giving him your login doesn't just give him access to your grades, but potentially also gives him access to your homework assignments, emails, student financial account...

author: listener
text: It sounds like you have enough to worry about without your parents giving you so much extra pressure.

text: It is challenging to maintain motivation at all times, anxiety and depression can set in which can make interacting with others a  struggle, it can lead us to do things that make us not feel good and we become isolated.

author: listener
text: This ends up feeding into a cycle that maintains the anxiety/depression loop  and can be really challenging to step out of it.

author: speaker
text: I sleep a lot. Music changes my mood. I cry every Wednesday. My mind is like a maze that even I get lost in. I don't usually feel my true emotions, but instead, I get fake mirrored ones.

author: listener
text: What happens in your life on Wednesdays that you feel like crying?

author: listener
text: Crying is natural.

author: listener
text: Crying on Wednesdays may also be natural if some type of regular event or situation comes up for you then that you don't like, feel oppressed by and have no way of avoiding.

author: speaker
text: I have twin toddlers. I experienced a death of loved one prior to giving birth. I had a horrible break up with the father. People told him he was using me for money. My ex-boyfriend had extreme meltdowns every day for three years. I’m always alone with no friends.

author: listener
text: First, let me say that you are a survivor and a warrior.

author: listener
text: Managing 1 child by yourself is difficult, but twins is a whole different ballgame.

author: speaker
text: It hit me early this year. Depression. I live alone. I got 2 kids that I've put ahead of my pain for so long, I keep at it so they have a dad. I don't know if I can anymore. I want to honestly, it just hurts so fucking bad right now.

author: listener
text: Winter is always hard for me to get through also.

author: listener
text: I've even tried a happy lamp, but it hasn't been enough, really.

author: listener
text: Even though it is true that you need to be there for your kids, wouldn't trying to get some help for your depression be a gift for your children as well as for you?

author: listener
text: To keep going for your kids and doing everything for them ahead of your pain really takes a lot.

author: speaker
text: I have no friends, no hobbies, and no interest in anything. I get annoyed with everything and everyone. I am always tired, i can sleep 8 hrs or 12 hrs and im still tired. I don't know what to do. Is this normal?

author: listener
text: Hello, and thank you for your question.

author: listener
text: It certainly sounds like you don't like how things are going.

author: speaker
text: I have no friends, no hobbies, and no interest in anything. I get annoyed with everything and everyone. I am always tired, i can sleep 8 hrs or 12 hrs and im still tired. I don't know what to do. Is this normal?

author: listener
text: Hello, and thank you for your question.

author: listener
text: It certainly sounds like you don't like how things are going.

author: listener
text: Here are a few thoughts and ideas:1.

author: listener
text: If you haven't seen a primary care provider in a while, you may want to.

author: listener
text: There are health conditions that can affect your mood and energy levels, even at your age.

author: listener
text: It doesn't hurt to get checked out.

author: listener
text: If they find the cause, they may be able to treat it and improve the symptoms.

author: listener
text: In addition, most primary care providers are trained to be able to manage medication for patients who have mild, moderate, and sometimes severe depression.

author: listener
text: So, don't be surprised if your primary care doctor offers to put you on an anti-depressant if they diagnose you with depression.

author: listener
text: Medication is not the only way to treat depression, but sometimes it is necessary depending on different factors.

author: listener
text: You may want to consider counseling, since it is another effective way to treat depression.

author: listener
text: A counselor will help you explore the factors that may be leading to depressive symptoms in the first place.

author: listener
text: This could include thoughts, behaviors, beliefs, life experiences, and other things.

author: listener
text: Finally, to answer your question about whether these feelings are "normal. "

author: speaker
text: I've been alone and unwanted my entire life and I'm extremely depressed. It made my childhood really painful. I can't go through a day without breaking down, I can't work like this, and treatment isn't going to help being in such a horrible environment. Can anyone help me figure out how I can get out of this place?

author: listener
text: You're right - treatment does not fix horrible situations.

author: speaker
text: I have a lot on my mind, but all I want to do is stay locked in my room and not socialize with anyone. Why do I feel so alone?

author: listener
text: It has been said that depression is often the result of a blocked goal.

author: listener
text: Often people struggle with both anxiety and depression but have difficulty determining which is the most important issue.

author: listener
text: For some, depression is the result of frequently blocked goals and when their predominant issues are evaluated, they discover that they are anxious (worried) about a lot of areas in their life but seem to find no relief.

author: listener
text: When there is no relief and there have been numerous attempts (either in their mind or in practical application) to resolve the anxiety, depression is often the result.

author: listener
text: In this type of case, depression is not the main or underlying issue.

author: listener
text: The anxiety is the underlying issue.

author: listener
text: Having "a lot on my mind" sounds like anxiety.

author: listener

author: speaker
text: Right now, I am taking Calculus I, Chemistry, and Physics. I never really took Physics in my life, and SHIT. Physics is mainly math word problems, which I didn't really know about. I wanna learn Physics, but just don't know how to learn it properly...I feel like failing Physics on purpose for now and retaking it in the next quarter to focus more on Calculus and Chemistry.

author: listener
text: I had a flawless freshmen year grades wise, but had a very tough year psychologically.

author: listener
text: As a result, my grades went down exponentially , up until I got to my senior year.

author: listener
text: I managed to find a path ahead, even though I'm not even sure what I want for my life this late in college.

author: listener
text: Heck, you may even end up loving it later on.

author: speaker
text: Thanks for the advice. As an introvert, I don't know how to befriend people properly. It just feels awkward for me and I don't know how to keep conversations going...Like the only ones I know in college so far are from my high school.

author: listener
text: The key is in finding the right people, people like you.

author: speaker
text: I've had posttraumatic stress disorder for years without my parents ever finding out. I want to overcome it, but it’s so vivid, it’s like it’s happening again. I'm scared and paranoid. I have depression, which I have been struggling with since a young age.

author: listener
text: I understand that at times it’s difficult to share with our parents what we have been trough, due to fear of judgment or punishment; but I have noticed that keeping our experiences secret, intensifies them.

author: speaker
text: After having fallen into depression the number of friends I have has dramatically shrunk and my efforts, though limited has made it next to impossible to be with anyone. This feeling of worthlessness I have is soul crushing, I got a shitty, terrible education. It's taken me years to learn everything I missed and I'm trying to go back into adult education but my insomnia and depression are making it incredibly hard on me.

author: listener
text: >I can't stand the lie's that people say in the workplace especially in retail and I hate the fact there is no honour amongst anyone anymore.

author: speaker
text: I always see the worst end of things. My boyfriend and I aren't talking, and I swear he's leaving me. I keep failing my road test, and I see my future crumble. I have no desire for friends. I pushed my best friend away after Christmas, and I have no desire to fix it or make new friends. My aunt died, and I cry all the time, even if I burn my lunch.

author: listener
text: I really love that you're taking responsibility for your pessimism here.

author: listener
text: There's a modern parable about two young brothers.

author: listener
text: One child is in a room full of every toy you could imagine, and he's miserable; the other is in a room full of horse manure, and he's flinging it around with joy.

author: listener
text: So then someone comes and asks the first boy why he's so miserable, because he has so much.

author: listener
text: He says that he's missing the one toy that he really wants.

author: listener
text: Then the brother is asked why he's so happy in a room full of manure, and he says "With all this sh-t, there's gotta be a pony in here somewhere!

author: listener
text: "Happiness is a state of mind, and I hear you saying that you used to be happy, so maybe this means you believe it's possible.

author: listener
text: That's a wonderful start.

author: listener
text: Research on depression shows us that it is very linked to pessimism.

author: listener
text: You say "I always see the worst end of things".

author: speaker
text: I was in a situation with a guy. He’s my brother’s friend and kind of like a brother to me. He invited me over to hang out, and then came on to me. I was instantly terrified to say no, and I gave in. I don't know what's wrong with me. I can't figure out why I'm afraid to say no. This is giving me a lot of guilt and depression.

author: listener
text: Hi Tennessee, There is nothing wrong with you.

author: listener
text: There are many good reasons why you didn't say no.

author: listener
text: You didn't say no because you were caught off guard and unprepared; there is no place in life that teaches girls or boys how to manage it when someone crashes a sexual boundary.

author: listener
text: You also live in a culture where girls are encouraged to be cooperative and not upset people, and to put the needs of other people first.

author: listener
text: You instinctively want people to like you, and people can be very coercive sexually.

author: speaker
text: I started working again, I'm about to pass all my classes for this semester, and I'm slowly opening back up to people and willing to try new relationships. And yet...  And yet I feel it's still there inside of me. When something bad happens, when I get sad, I can sometimes feel myself succumbing to despair before I get a hold of myself. It's not *natural* yet... What if I allow it to come back?

author: listener
text: A few days ago I was feeling really sad and as always, I resorted to the internet in order to feel better or at least understood, and I found a post of yours.

author: listener
text: One does not get rid of depression that easily, is a long fight.

author: speaker
text: They don't go away, and I feel like I'm going crazy. Does that ever stop? Can it be a symptom of medication?

author: listener
text: Since you realize that hearing voices in your head is not usual for you, then definitely there is a problematic situation happening within your awareness of who you are.

author: speaker
text: Nobody seems to understand how I feel about things. Sometimes I get so down about things that I cry and feel hopeless, and then hours later, I'm completely fine. I feel helpless. It's like I'm always sad or angry in the background, and sometimes I don't even know why. I almost never feel alright.

author: listener
text: You would get a lot of value from seeing a councillor once a week for a while.

author: listener
text: Compared to most it sounds like you just need to tweak a few things to get your life back on track.

author: listener
text: With friends and family around you you're on a better start than most who come to this sub looking for help.

author: speaker
text: Thanks. I started seeing a counselor this semester . . . I guess I'm just discouraged by how slow the whole process is.

author: listener
text: It's taken all these years to scramble the egg, not going to fix years of destruction over night.

author: listener

author: listener
text: However, if they are totally  unexpressed, anger turn inward and shift into depression.

author: listener
text: When she yells at you, what do you do?

author: listener
text: Is this the moment that you feel the most angry?

author: listener
text: I wouldn't be surprised; anger is a normal response to someone yelling at you.

author: listener
text: Something about anger.

author: listener
text: it's often there to cover up our more vulnerable emotions.

author: listener
text: Under the anger I wonder if you feel worthless, powerless, scared, unloved.

author: listener
text: Part of the trick to reducing anger is identifying those other emotions and expressing them.

author: listener
text: You say you don't know how to deal with life, and I think maybe you mean you don't know how to deal with emotions.

author: speaker
text: I've been having this ongoing problem for most of my life now. I am a young adult, and right now, driving and even being a passenger gives me terrible panic attacks and anxiety. I can't ride in the backseat or the front seat with the safety belt on. I have to lean the seat back a bit because the pressure on my back terrifies me. I miss so many opportunities to go places with friends and family because of my fears of having a panic attack. My family offers little to no support. They think it's fake or "all in my head." It makes me feel guilty and at times depressed to the point where I'd rather never wake up anymore. I am not self-harming, I just feel meaningless. This constant fear has taken over my thoughts and my life. I was such a happy person. I want my life back. I want to travel with my friends and family again, but I don't know how. I've almost given up hope on getting better and just accepting the fact that I'll live with this anxiety forever.

author: listener
text: Not having support from your family for such a significant problem, is a problem itself.

author: listener
text: How about your friends, are any of them nurturing or treat you kindly when you bring up that you've got this problem?

author: listener
text: Are any of your friends willing to accommodate the fact that right now you've got panic attacks from driving and being a passenger?

author: listener
text: Maybe being and feeling accepted while you're in this current phase of your life, would help diminish the panic attacks.

author: listener
text: If no support is coming to you, then a next step would be to evaluate the relationships in your life and to develop standards and expectations of others, especially that they are considerate of your great need at this time.

author: listener
text: Its possible you are bearing the emotional burden of a lot more people in your life than yourself.

author: speaker

author: listener
text: People will tell you time and time again that you're worth it, but it's not this depressed version that has worth.

author: speaker
text: My mind know that i can go, just move and shit will get done. But it just won't happen, time and time again that has happened. But I know because i have watched it many times and i know that it's inevitably going to happen again. I just feel my motivation draining and nothing gets done. I know this is a sad attempt to make people feel sorry for me and im not requiring anything from anybody.

author: listener
text: Along the way, you'll catch a ball to the face, get swamped with paperwork, and embarrass yourself trying to make someone laugh, but hell, will it be worth it to actually *live*?

author: speaker
text: At school, it feels like I've lost all my friends, and I've been really weird with my sleeping patterns. I used to cut myself, and I really want to again, but I change in the locker rooms because I don’t want anybody to see. I get ticked off easy and overreact. At night, I’m very depressed and listen to sad music and all that sort of stuff. Please help me. I just want to be happy again, and I feel like I’m starting to fake a smile at school.

author: listener
text: As silly as it may sound, making sure that we are getting the right amount of *restful* sleep is very important when we are feeling low.

author: listener
text: The reason for this is the lack of proper sleep significantly affects our ability to problem solve and critically evaluate our situation and can lead to a domino effect in our thinking.

author: speaker
text:
My fiancée suffers from severe anxiety and depression. She has had it most of her life. Her anxiety in public places is the worst. It gets to points where she can't breathe or move. Sometimes, she won't even go to the restroom, so she will hold in her pee until her stomach hurts or she pees herself. She curls up in corners at the mall and has panic attacks. She won't eat or drink in public. If she isn't having a panic attack or crying, she's clinging to me and avoiding everything and everyone. Her depression flares up out of nowhere and causes her to become very suicidal and self-harming. She get really sick from anxiety and scared to the point that I can't even get her to eat, drink, leave the bed, or go outside. She always tells me how she grew up around so much fighting and fear that it makes her scared of loud sounds, yelling, conflict, and even talking to strangers in public. She will refuse to go to a store unless I am with her to talk to the cashier for her. She is so scared that I can't even get her to drive. She doesn't want to get her license because she's scared of trying to drive.
   Some people have recommended medication, but I believe it's just going to cover up her illness and not solve it. I don't want my fiancée pumped with drugs. I believe a psychiatric service dog would be the best bet for her. When we first met my poodle, it would calm her down a lot. She took the dog out every time we went out, and she seemed much calmer and happier. She slowly would eat, and the dog seemed to make her feel a lot better. I am worried and want to help her without medication.

author: listener
text: It sounds like you have been a positive support for your fiancee.

author: listener
text: There is no doubt that this situation is a great challenge for the both of you.

author: listener
text: While it may feel like you are responsible for her health and happiness, it is important that you understand that you, on your own, won't be able to resolve her mental health issues.

author: listener
text: Based on what you have explained, it sounds like she needs to get a medical and/or psychiatric evaluation.

author: speaker
text:
I am in high school and have been facing anxiety issues lately. Whenever I get close to being in a relationship, some kind of anxiety takes over and keeps me from the relationship. This anxiety causes me depression at times and even makes me want to vomit. While a semi-relationship should be joyous, for me, it’s an emotional nightmare I can’t get to the bottom of. I’ve had this before and had to leave the semi-relationship to avoid throwing up every time I made contact with my crush. What could be the reason behind this? Is it massive nerve problems? Is it a fear of a bad relationship?
   While I’m not quite ready to be in one anyway, I want to get to the bottom of this for a brighter future in which I can be in one. I don’t take medications and have no desire to, I have read forums, and I’ve talked about the issue with my sister who has faced similar problems.

author: listener
text: Hi Helena,I felt a bit sad when I read this.

author: listener
text: This is a new term for me.

author: listener
text: "semi-relationship".

author: listener
text: What does it mean?

author: listener
text: I know that today's culture for young people is more of a "hook-up" culture than a dating one.

author: listener
text: Maybe that means that you develop connections to people but you keep yourself from hoping for a full relationship because no one is doing that anymore.

author: speaker
text: I was married to a narcissist sociopath for 10 years. During that time I was a general manager. I used to help him financially and in other ways when we were together. But things began to change. He emotionally and sexually drained me. I lost my spirit. I used to be a very happy person but now I am a loner. I left him and moved to another state. Currently, I'm working as a server which makes me believe less in myself. I feel pity for myself a lot but don't know what to do. When I have money problems, he does not help me. He actually enjoys seeing me have a hard time in my life. I need help.

author: listener
text: Congratulations on leaving your marriage!

author: listener
text: It is ok and natural to feel sadness, loss, uncertainty in direction, hurt, resulting from ending the marriage.

author: listener
text: Possibly what you consider "pity" is a combination of these feelings.

author: listener
text: Be kind and caring toward who you are since you just put yourself through a major separation and need time to clear out the old emotions that connected you to your ex.

author: listener
text: There is very, very little chance of him helping you since he lacks compassion and empathy.

author: listener
text: More likely any help he gave would be in order to manipulate you.

author: listener
text: Maybe for now your server job is ok do you have more time to concentrate on taking care of your emotions.

author: speaker
text: My depression and anxiety stemmed from what I think was fear of becoming an adult. Eventually, after a gap year, I somehow slowly overcame my depression and anxiety. If anyone shares similar experiences or feelings about fear or life please share!

author: listener
text: I wish there was a pill or some magic fairy dust that could prevent me from feeling anxious.

author: listener
text: But therein lies our personal issue with anxiety I imagine.

author: listener
text: Perhaps anxiety isn't something to prevent or eliminate, but something to use and benefit from.

author: speaker
text:
When I'm in large crowds I get angry and I just can't deal with people. I don't really like other people (I prefer animals) they make me nervous and scared.
   I lay awake at night thinking and having conversations in my head and i almost always end up making myself feel terrible and crying, I have more conversions in my head than I do with actual people.    I don't know what's wrong with me and why I feel this way. What should I do?

author: listener
text: What you are experiencing is totally normal and these emotions mean you are human!

author: listener
text: Humans are social creatures who were created to be in connection with others, but sometimes our life experiences or genetics can make that more difficult for some of us.

author: listener
text: It is possible that these reactions are based on negative reactions you have had with others in the past, maybe your family, or other traumatic interactions with others.

author: listener
text: It is also possible that they are caused by an underlying condition such as anxiety or depression, which may cause you to be more uncomfortable around others or annoyed by others.

author: listener
text: Some people are also more bothered by crowded spaces, loud interactions, and the actions of others.

author: listener
text: Of course you prefer animals (me too!

author: listener
text: ), they provide unconditional love and support, do not judge you, and do not require you to have conversations with them.

author: listener
text: The fact that you have conversations in your head at night tells me that although you say you do not like people, you are craving some social connection.

author: listener
text: Being in crowds can provoke anxiety (one of the symptoms of anxiety is irritability or anger, like you described).

author: listener
text: For some people, that's just because of their personality (if you tend to be more introverted, being around lot of people is really draining).

author: listener
text: For others, it can point to a diagnosis of social anxiety.

author: listener
text: I've read some truly incredible things in my time here, all sorts of poems and essays, but this is definitely by far *the best* piece of writing I have ever seen in this sub.

author: speaker
text: Thank you. Writing is my most important self-coping mechanism. Like anyone else I've produced my share of pitiful doggerel and mangy essays that just sound like whining afterwards. I'm in a very rough spot right now and having difficulty putting virtual pen to paper, but I stumbled on this old piece and wished I'd realised how much it is like my experience of depression at the time and wanted to share. I'm glad it resonates with someone else too.

author: listener
text: Oh I forgot to mention that not only is it amazingly written but also I relate to every word.

author: listener
text: I write too  and also usually struggle when I'm feeling low.

author: listener
text: It does help a lot to read and enjoy old pieces in those times.

author: listener
text: I hope you're resisting the vicious cycle of: not writing because feeling awful ---> feeling awful because not writing.

author: listener
text: Anyway, thank you for sharing this!

author: listener
text: People are  beside me trying to dig out as well, but all we know how to do is to dig a deeper hole.

author: listener
text: It's an incredibly lonely feeling to know people are so close to me, yet so distant as well.

author: speaker
text: Sometimes normal people things make me feel conflicted. Funny thing is, I'm the one with faith issues and yet I'm the one feeling guilty even thinking about these things. I can't be happy if I can't make others happy or proud of me. But doing what makes me happy most likely would make people  detest me. People think I'm weird.

text: People who say the slightest thing criticizing Islam gets vilified. Even if no one says anything. author: speaker
text: I'm dealing with imposter syndrome in graduate school. I know that by all accounts I am a phenomenal graduate student, and that I am well-published. I am well liked by students and faculty alike. And yet I cannot shake the feeling that I'm going to be found out as a fraud.    How can I get over this feeling?

author: listener
text: It would be very helpful to identify with you eventual pattern where the imposter syndrome is more or less present.

author: listener
text: Are there specific situations where you've noticed the feelings of "I'm going to be found out as a fraud" becoming more strong?

author: listener
text: It seems that shaking this feeling is very important to you.

text: Hello.

text: First, I am so sorry you are experiencing these feelings.

author: listener
text: They can be intense, I will do my best to offer some suggestions or thoughts that I hope will be helpful to you.

author: listener
text: There could be a number of things occurring.

author: listener
text: Therapy is a delicate, private decision and I would first like to commend you for the fact that you are not giving up, that you are working to figure this out, and make this work, it sounds like you are engaged and motivated to receive support from a professional, your continued  dedication and motivation will take you far.

author: speaker

text: I'm really sorry that you've had such a hard time with your friend.

author: listener
text: It's really lovely that you want to be there for him, a good support network is really important regarding recovery, but what's equally important is self-care.

author: listener
text: If you get too swept into other person's problems, that might get you in a really bad way and that's not going to help either of you.

author: speaker
text: I've gone to a couple therapy sessions so far and still everytime I walk in I get nervous and shaky. Is this normal? Should I still be feeling like this?

author: listener
text: Hi there, Thank you for your question.

author: listener
text: It's absolutely ok to feel nervous going to therapy.

author: listener
text: I have experienced anxiety going to see my own therapist.

author: listener
text: There can be a few reasons why you might feel this way.

author: listener
text: First, it is always unnerving to see a person who is a stranger and to share intimate things with that stranger.

author: listener
text: You mentioned it has only been a couple of sessions.

author: listener
text: As children, we might have bad experiences opening up to others.

author: listener
text: Someone might bully or ridicule us, and that experience can stay with us for a long time, making it extra scary to share our intimate feelings and thoughts with others.

author: listener
text: If this the case, as you continue with your sessions and have positive interactions with your therapists, this anxiety will subside with time and you will re-learn that it is safe to share.

text: OK first things first.

author: listener
text: We have to think of your safety and take care of those thoughts of hurting yourself.

text: Yes, this is a major problem for you and can cause anxiety and depression.

author: listener

author: listener

author: speaker
text:
I have been with my boyfriend for more than a year. He recently got a new job and travels a lot. I’m not used to him being gone all the time. I feel as though he has forgotten about me because he does not talk with me as much and doesn’t keep me up to date on everything that he does throughout the day, which he used to.
 I feel lost, sad and unwanted. This is really a tough new challenge. I just want to break up with him, but I love him so much. I don’t know why he is acting this way lately. I believe I have separation anxiety. Is there anything that I can do to help me cope with this while he is out of town?

author: listener
text: In a way, yes, you have separation anxiety.

author: speaker
text:
I have been with my boyfriend for more than a year. He recently got a new job and travels a lot. I’m not used to him being gone all the time. I feel as though he has forgotten about me because he does not talk with me as much and doesn’t keep me up to date on everything that he does throughout the day, which he used to.
 I feel lost, sad and unwanted. This is really a tough new challenge. I just want to break up with him, but I love him so much. I don’t know why he is acting this way lately. I believe I have separation anxiety. Is there anything that I can do to help me cope with this while he is out of town?

author: listener
text: In a way, yes, you have separation anxiety.

author: listener
text: It's normal in a relationship for us to slow down a bit with the attachment behaviours that establish and deepen love and connection.

author: listener
text: So, just because your boyfriend isn't talking as much or keeping you up-to-date doesn't necessarily mean what you fear it means.

text:
I have been with my boyfriend for more than a year. He recently got a new job and travels a lot. I’m not used to him being gone all the time. I feel as though he has forgotten about me because he does not talk with me as much and doesn’t keep me up to date on everything that he does throughout the day, which he used to.
 I feel lost, sad and unwanted. This is really a tough new challenge. I just want to break up with him, but I love him so much. I don’t know why he is acting this way lately. I believe I have separation anxiety. Is there anything that I can do to help me cope with this while he is out of town?

author: listener
text: In a way, yes, you have separation anxiety.

author: listener
text: It's normal in a relationship for us to slow down a bit with the attachment behaviours that establish and deepen love and connection.

author: listener
text: So, just because your boyfriend isn't talking as much or keeping you up-to-date doesn't necessarily mean what you fear it means.

author: listener
text: that he's forgotten about you or loves you less.

author: listener
text: It could mean quite the opposite.

author: listener
text: that he's focused on being successful in his new job and impressing you.

author: listener
text: He may think he's loving you more, but you feel loved less.

author: listener
text: You have two jobs to do here.

author: listener
text: The first is to manage your anxiety by "talking back" to the thoughts it puts into your head.

author: listener
text: It sounds like "It's normal to be insecure, but I have tons of evidence that he loves me and that I mean the world to him. "

text: Chances are, you accepted this opportunity knowing that sometimes, you feel heightened levels of anxiety while traveling (or at least, people are telling you this is true) Rather than working towards how to stop it from happening, it might make more sense to prepare for if it does: often, when we know how we might deal with a situation, the situation doesn't manifest.

I just took a job that requires me to travel far away from home. My family and I really need this job.
   People keep telling me I have "anxiety" and I'm terrified of having an anxiety attack on the road. This is all new to me. What can I do?

author: listener
text: There are lots of things you can do, but first: Congratulations on your new job!

author: listener
text: Commuting long distances can be stressful, but there are some things you can do.

author: speaker
text:
I just took a job that requires me to travel far away from home. My family and I really need this job.
   People keep telling me I have "anxiety" and I'm terrified of having an anxiety attack on the road. This is all new to me. What can I do?

author: listener
text: There are lots of things you can do, but first: Congratulations on your new job!

author: listener
text: Commuting long distances can be stressful, but there are some things you can do.

author: listener
text: First, make sure that your seating arrangement in your car is comfortable.

author: listener
text: If you are driving long distances on a regular basis, you want to make sure that your body is in a comfortable position.

author: listener
text: Second, select some music or podcasts that work for you, rather than against you.

author: listener
text: Soothing music is good, as well as inspirational podcasts.

author: listener
text: Alternatively, listening to books can be a great way to spend the time, improve your mood, and find inspiration.

author: listener
text: Third, make sure that you have plenty of time for your commute.

author: listener
text: If the drive normally takes you 30 minutes, plan on 45 (or if it's 45 minutes, plan on an hour).

author: listener
text: This way you won't be rushed, can take your time, can focus on your driving, and if traffic is a bit backed up, you've got plenty of time to reach your destination.

author: listener
text: Finally, if you do find yourself being anxious in a way that impedes your driving, pull over to the side of the road, take some deep breaths, and sit with your feelings.

author: listener
text: Take a deep drink of water.

author: listener
text: Consider jotting your feelings down in a journal.

author: listener
text: If its safe, get out of the car and walk around a bit, stretching you muscles and breathing in the air.

text: I never know when the next urgent project is going to come up, and I never know when my next mistake and lecture are coming. Work just feels like a huge dark cloud over my life. I don’t know if they know how bad it is. I just don’t know.

author: listener
text: Seems like I can only last 10 years and then I self-sabotage and get bored/paranoid/down about work.

author: listener
text: However, if a job is really making you that miserable, definitely find something else .

author: speaker
text: I worry I’m a burden to my family and husband. I worry all the time that no one likes me. I don’t want to be the problem person, I just want to be me. Anyone out there understand how this feels?

author: listener
text: I do.

author: listener
text: When I feel very bad I like to stay alone and away from everybody.

author: listener
text: So I am not hurting anyone and they are not annoying me.

author: listener
text: I don't think that feeling well forever is possible for me but if you keep trying and you keep having the desire to try... maybe you will be.

author: listener
text: Maybe not happy forever, but maybe happier than if you didn't try.

author: speaker
text: I am a really shy person. I'm currently in a graduate program which requires lots of presentations, but they always make me feel stressed out and less confident. How can I get more confident?

author: listener
text: A good way to start is the language or "self talk" that is happening inside your mind.

author: listener
text: Looking at your question, when it is said that the presentations "make me feel stress" you are giving the responsibility of the stress to the presentations and taking that away from your self.

author: speaker
text: I have a fear of something and I want to face that fear to overcome it, but I don't know how. What can I do?

author: listener
text: Fear is a part of life.

author: listener
text: In fact, our five main emotions are joy, fear, sadness, shame, and anger.

author: listener
text: We tend to spend a lot of time and energy running away from or trying to get rid of most of those emotions and the more we do that, the more we set ourselves up for failure and disappointment.

author: listener
text: As a result of viewing our human emotions as "bad" or "wrong," we often get caught up in a trap of thinking we have to overcome them or get rid of them before we can do what matters to us.

author: listener
text: In reality, you can do what is important to you while having your fears!

author: listener
text: My question for you is, what would you do if this fear was completely gone?

author: listener
text: What behaviors would you have if you were the ideal you?

author: listener
text: What skills, knowledge, or personal qualities would you develop?

author: listener
text: What kind of relationships would you have?

author: listener
text: I imagine your fear has kept you from achieving those goals because your mind tells you you can't do it until the fear is gone.

author: speaker
text: I don't remember when the voices in my head started, but I remember Hearing them when I was little.    I know it's not normal to hear voices that aren't your own. I fight the voices and I want them to stop. They've been here so long and I want them gone. How can I make the voices stop?

author: listener
text: This isn't something you can do on your own.

author: listener
text: If you haven't already, you need to see a medical doctor ASAP to rule out medical causes for this.

author: listener
text: Many diseases, illnesses, and conditions can cause hallucinations.

author: listener
text: In the elderly, sometimes it's something as simple as a urinary tract infection.

author: listener
text: Some medicines may have that side effect as well.

author: listener
text: However, you say you've been hearing them since you were little.

author: speaker
text: I've been dealing with this for years. My mom thinks I'm overly emotional and refuses to offer any help, like therapy or seeing a doctor. She's seen me when I'm having a panic attack and just said I was faking for attention or that I'm a hypochondriac. I just want to get better.

author: listener
text: I don't know how old you are, but in Pennsylvania, if you are over 14, you can have therapy without your parents' consent.

author: listener
text: If you are young enough to use their insurance, that could be complicated, but depending on the state, there may be ways to work around that as well.

author: listener
text: If transportation is a problem, call a local mental health agency and see if they can connect you with assistance.

author: listener
text: In the meantime, try searching for a phone helpline in the county where you live.

author: listener
text: They may be able to help you figure out where you can get help.

author: listener
text: Another idea is that if you are in school, your guidance counselor may be able to provide links to where you can go for help.

author: listener
text: He or she may also be able to give you more specific ideas to help with your panic attacks.

author: listener
text: I know you said your mom refuses to offer help, which included seeing a doctor, but I wonder if she trusts the doctors that is your primary care physician (also called a family doctor) who you see when you have a minor medical ailment that may need medication.

text: I constantly have this urge to throw away all my stuff. It’s constantly on my mind and makes me feel anxious. I don’t sleep because I’m thinking about something I can get rid of. I don’t know why I do it. I started years ago when I lived with my dad then I stopped when I moved in with my mom. Years later, it has started again.

author: listener
text: Since you wrote that you noticed a change in your throwing away urge when you changed with which parent you lived, would you feel that throwing away things is connected to wanting to be done with certain areas of influence with either parent?

author: listener
text: Play in your mind with the metaphor of "throwing away" and whatever associations you feel toward this.

author: listener
text: Are you feeling alarmed or freed, by throwing away things?

author: listener
text: I'm only suggesting these, not telling you that they apply necessarily.

author: listener
text: Anxiety comes up when people feel helpless to manage a meaningful part of their lives.

author: listener
text: So pay attention whether your stuff represents difficult scenarios or phases of your growing up years.

author: listener
text: Possibly you are trying to rid yourself of painful feelings which were part of your early years' relationship with either parent.

author: listener
text: Basically, sounds as though you are trying to establish a clearer sense of who you are and the throwing away part is a means of discovering who you are, once all the clutter is released.

text: I write to respond to your recent inquiry for possible increase in self-esteem and positive behavioral change regarding motivation for a new job.

text: It appears you were close to her in many ways and she had a great influence in your life.

author: listener
text: I write to respond to your recent inquiry for possible increase in self-esteem and positive behavioral change regarding motivation for a new job.

author: listener
text: First of all, please try to allow yourself some time for grief of the loss of your dear grandmother.

author: listener
text: It appears you were close to her in many ways and she had a great influence in your life.

author: listener
text: The grief process of anger, denial, despair and acceptance may be a part of what is keeping you feeling "stuck" in a cycle of not feeling motivated to find work at this time.

author: listener
text: Perhaps your mind is constantly fighting this grief?

author: listener
text: Death can be a "traumatic" experience for some people and is considered a great loss, thus the grief process may continue to be a part of your world for a time but hopefully not keep you "stuck" on a long-term basis.

author: listener
text: I would try to reach out to a counselor to discuss this grief process at a deeper level to discern whether her death is part of why you feel this way.

author: speaker
text: I feel like I hate myself physically and emotionally sometimes. How can I start accepting myself and be more confident?

author: listener
text: The answer would require a more in-depth knowledge of you and your situation.

author: listener
text: A lot of times, these feelings are the result of the people in your life treating you a certain way.

author: listener
text: You internalize it and accept it as your reality.

author: listener
text: The first step is to evaluate the people close to you, especially your parents.

author: listener
text: Even if you are an adult, think back to your childhood.

author: listener
text: Children who grow up in an unstable home often grow up to be adults with insecurities and emotional problems.

author: listener
text: The obvious, such as being abused, can certainly lead to a person having little to no confidence and self esteem, but there are other situations that might surprise you to hear they can be damaging to a person.

author: listener
text: You may have never been physically or sexually abused, but what about emotionally?

author: listener
text: Were you yelled at, berated, put down?

author: listener
text: Were you told you'd never amount to anything?

author: listener
text: Were you compared to siblings and felt like you always fell short, couldn't live up to expectations?

author: listener
text: When you hear something over and over again, you start to believe it.

author: listener
text: Maybe you weren't yelled at.

author: listener
text: Maybe it was the opposite.

author: listener
text: Studies show that children who grow up with a parent who is depressed show signs of emotional neglect.

author: listener
text: A chronically depressed mother, for example, may have seemed cold, detached, emotionless.

author: listener
text: She may have been less likely to show interest in a child's life, not give praise for accomplishments or show support by going to ballgames or performances.

author: listener
text: If one of your family members were chronically ill while you were growing up, chances are, a lot of the attention went to them, which could have led to your needs not being met.

author: speaker
text: I'm a male in my 20s. My girlfriend is in her late 30s. She's great. She's funny and smart, she has a big heart, and we have an excellent sex life. She recently moved in with me partially because she wanted to and partially because she had no place to go. We fight a lot. It’s mostly my fault, I must admit. She doesn't like my insecurity and lack of trust I have for her. I have trust issues. Also, I can't fathom why a woman like her is with me, so I'm always dreading when a better dude will come along. I don't think she's happy. She's very submissive and she loves me very much, but also the fact that she has nowhere to go must be influencing her decision to stay. I love her so much, but my jealousy is not likely to diminish. I never believed in the whole "If you love them, let them go," but I do now. I really want her to be happy. Should I end it with her? She has no place to go so I feel like I can’t break up with her. I’m literally trapped.

author: listener
text: Hi Fort Worth,  I applaud your awareness and insight into the relationship.

author: listener
text: Most of us come into relationships carrying old baggage and although you can't change her,  what you can do, is change yourself.

author: listener
text: We can usually begin to understand ourselves better in the context of our own upbringings.

author: listener
text: That is where we learn what a relationship looks like and it is often not the best teacher.

author: listener
text: I wonder about your jealously, insecurity, feeling trapped and a lack of trust.

author: speaker
text: I'm a male in my 20s. My girlfriend is in her late 30s. She's great. She's funny and smart, she has a big heart, and we have an excellent sex life. She recently moved in with me partially because she wanted to and partially because she had no place to go. We fight a lot. It’s mostly my fault, I must admit. She doesn't like my insecurity and lack of trust I have for her. I have trust issues. Also, I can't fathom why a woman like her is with me, so I'm always dreading when a better dude will come along. I don't think she's happy. She's very submissive and she loves me very much, but also the fact that she has nowhere to go must be influencing her decision to stay. I love her so much, but my jealousy is not likely to diminish. I never believed in the whole "If you love them, let them go," but I do now. I really want her to be happy. Should I end it with her? She has no place to go so I feel like I can’t break up with her. I’m literally trapped.

text: Unfortunately, a lot of adults use shame as a motivator for kids.

author: listener

author: listener
text: When was the first time you remember feeling a lot of shame, as in "I'm bad", or "I'm worthless"?

author: listener
text: Is there a younger version of you who is still feeling shame over something that wasn't your fault?

author: listener
text: Sometimes shame shadows are connected to an absent or hurtful parent, sexual abuse or some family loss or trauma.

author: listener
text: If so, picture yourself at that age.

author: listener
text: Can you tell your child self that whatever horrible thing happened to them isn't their fault?

author: listener
text: Can you have compassion for that child who first felt shame or had shame heaped on them?

author: listener
text: That's your first goal.

author: listener
text: to go to the source of the shame and heal that child's wound with compassion.

author: listener
text: What happens to children is never their fault (and fault is a pretty useless concept anyway).

author: listener
text: Once you take the layers of old "I'm bad" shame off, the load is lighter and you can use self talk to further reduce the shame.

author: listener
text: Here are some things you can say to yourself.

author: listener
text: every day.

author: listener
text: I'm human and that's okay.

author: listener
text: I don't have to be perfect.

author: listener
text: I can have compassion for my mistakes.

author: listener
text: I can feel proud that I'm facing my mistake and making things right.

author: listener
text: I deserve forgiveness and compassion, and I have that for other people too.

author: listener
text: There's no purpose to holding on to shame.

author: listener
text: I can learn from my mistakes and move forward.

author: listener
text: Everyone makes mistakes.

author: listener
text: Other people don't want me to carry this shame around.

text: The decision to end a relationship is often very difficult.

author: listener
text: It is important that you are aware of your personal "deal breakers".

author: listener
text: Some common deal breakers are abuse of any kind (physical, verbal, sexual, or emotional) or substance abuse; however, anything that is detrimental to your well being can be considered a deal breaker.

author: listener
text: I know of a young woman who broke up with her boyfriend because he decided to adopt a pet cat and she is highly allergic.

author: listener
text: For her, having a cat was a deal breaker !

author: listener
text: Healthy relationships enhance personal growth, and  we enhance our spiritual and emotional wellbeing by collaborating with our partner to work through problems and overcome challenges.

text: My guess is that you would not be questioning whether or not to end your relationship if things were going smoothly.

text: If so, is it an option to talk about this with him?

author: listener
text: If you decide to get back together, consider having some conversations about what your concerns are and taking about five minutes or so to listen to this guy's thoughts, feelings, etc.

text: Then see if you can repeat the essence of what he said to make sure you have it right.

author: listener
text: Then maybe you can ask some questions that you have and see if he is willing to listen.

text: When each of you is in the role of asking questions, try to ask them as if you are an investigative reporter trying to learn more about each other's experience.

text: If you are looking for information on coping with breaking up and you don't want to get back together or that's not an option, consider looking at how you define yourself and what is most important to you at this moment.

author: speaker

author: listener
text: Here are some things I'm wondering:Do you have close friends that you can talk to, trust, and who can be around sometimes when you're in between relationships?

author: listener
text: What do you like about yourself?

text: What are your strongest points?

text: Do you think you have been in relationships with controlling than in the past because it makes you feel as though you are worth something to them?

text: What kind of relationship you want to be in?

text: What are the top three or four attributes of the type of partner you want?

author: listener
text: What can you do to make yourself emotionally safe during your typical daily activities?

author: listener
text: Can you notice a list of things that you can control throughout a typical day?

author: listener
text: For example, you probably choose what to wear, what to eat, how to talk to others, how committed you are to school or work, etc.

author: listener
text: It also sounds as if it may be helpful to discover more about yourself in addition to what you look for in a partner.

text: Have you sued them yet?

author: speaker
text: In 2008 my former husband of 14 years walked away from my life and we've been separated ever since. We have always been together sexually and both have experienced sleeping with others. I stopped because I wanted my marriage to work out but he did not. If he stops sleeping with other women, can our marriage be saved? Or should we just part ways? I still care deeply about him after all that I did and he has done. But he is seeing someone else on and off for years now. Will our marriage still be saved if he decides that he wants to try to do so?

author: listener
text: Sorry to hear about the stress in your relationship.

author: listener
text: There is definite value in being clear as you are, about your own emotional investment in your husband and that you expect sexual exclusivity from him as part of the foundation of your marriage.

author: listener
text: Also positive is your awareness that only your husband is the one who must similarly decide his own standards of being sexually exclusive to you, or not.

author: listener
text: Whether your marriage can be saved depends on what each person is willing to accept about the other one.

author: listener
text: Is sleeping with other women the only criterion of what will satisfy you about being together with your husband?

author: listener
text: Love and care are not enough to make a marriage work.

author: listener
text: Partners need to be able to compromise and cooperate with each other.

author: listener
text: That you care for him definitely intensifies any emotion you feel toward your husband.

author: listener
text: It intensifies any frustration and sadness about the relationship too.

author: listener
text: Decide how much emotional sadness and hurt you're willing to tolerate and the reason you're willing to do so.

author: listener

author: listener
text: I think that it is normal to struggle to get your feet under you again after a divorce, especially after leaving a relationship that lasted 11 years, so try not to be too hard on yourself.

text: Have a ritual to begin the day:  Consider setting a one sentence intention and plan tasks for the day2.

text: Take the breaks you are offered.

text: This could lead you to feel inadequate in the relationship that can harm your relationship in the long-term.

author: listener
text: Based on what you are reporting and without knowing your wife's side of the story, I would say that you are raising 3 different concerns.

author: listener
text: One is that there seems to be some concern of infidelity from your wife that you feel is not justified.

author: listener
text: It may bear clarifying how each of you define "infidelity".

author: listener
text: Currently, there is no uniform definition of infidelity because it can emcompass a hook-up, chatroom texting, extensive phone calls to a female friend, viewing pornography, a massage with happy ending, physical intercourse, or intimate emotional sharing.

author: listener
text: Depending on whether any of these circumstances have occured, you may need to reflect whether there is any truth to what she may be accusing you of and for you to share with her your reasons for engaging in these activities.

author: listener
text: If there is no truth to it, then my clinical intuition is that she may be accusing you of infidelity as a way of saying, "I feel you distancing from me. "

author: listener
text: In other words, it's not so much about whether you are actually unfaithful but a statement of how she feels as she witnesses your distancing from her.

author: listener
text: Often times, accusing a partner of cheating is likened to a cry or a yearning for closeness.

author: listener
text: If so, what you want to do is to reflect to her that perhaps she is saying that you are unfaithful because she senses that you are moving away from her emotionally.

author: listener
text: If this is true, you may wish to share with her why you are pulling away and then discuss the kind of support you may need to feel closer to her again.

author: listener
text: Otherwise, if the focus becomes about who is right and who is wrong, the conversation will never touch at both of your core emotional needs.

author: listener
text: The second issue touches upon how to interpret calling someone a "sweetheart. "

author: listener
text: The term has been loosely used in a variety of contexts to mean "you're so sweet and kind", "my dear", or in a flirtatious manner to mean "sweetie. "

author: speaker

author: listener
text: The term has been loosely used in a variety of contexts to mean "you're so sweet and kind", "my dear", or in a flirtatious manner to mean "sweetie. "

author: listener
text: The intention behind the use is known only to the speaker.

author: listener
text: You may want to reflect in what context you meant to use the term and share it with your wife.

author: listener
text: If your wife overheard the comment not knowing your intentions or context, it is possible that she may have misinterpreted what you have said.

author: listener
text: If she finds the term disrespectful, it may be her way of expressing, "I want to be the important person in your life and if you call someone else a sweetheart it means that I am not valued as much. "

author: listener
text: Therefore, arguing about who has the right or wrong interpretation may be missing the mark.

author: listener
text: Rather, the issue is about how do you wish to treat or show consideration of each others feelings?

author: listener
text: You may wish to explore how do you show her that you value her and that she is important to you?

author: listener
text: Is saying "sweetheart" to another woman conducive to that or is it sending mixed messages to your wife?

author: listener
text: That said, if you have expressed and shown her that she is important to you on many occasions with open discussions and by understanding, accomodating and prioritizing her needs, then her actions may be a reflection of her personal insecurities.

author: speaker
text:
I've worked with this guy for about three years now, and I knew the first time I saw him that I was attracted. Over time, he became a very dear friend, and we talked about our relationship problems, family, dreams, and so on. There was always flirtation with us, and one day pretty recently, it progressed to making out. We agreed to keep it quiet, and we did, but in the back of my mind, I hoped it would become something more. It didn't, and three months later, I'm still not over it.
   I'm trying so hard to maintain the friendship because that's what he wants. We're no longer in the same office, which I thought would help me get over these feelings, but we still talk about work, and he's constantly touching me, so I'm still very drawn to him. He's a hugger and such a sweet guy, so I find myself fantasizing all the time about what could have been and what could still be, but he's clearly not interested. He's younger than me and prefers model types, but I see him checking me out a lot, which gives me hope. How do I get him out of my system and still maintain the friendship?

author: listener
text: It sounds like you have mixed feelings and motivations - which is understandable.

author: speaker
text: I was raped a couple months ago, Since then, along with other unfortunately events that have occurred, I have been having trouble feeling emotions. It's almost as if I'm a sociopath lacking any feeling. What can I do to change this?

author: listener
text: Hi!

author: listener
text: This is a great question!

author: listener
text: The term you are looking for is alexithymia, the inability to identify and describe emotions in the self.

author: listener
text: However, just because you are not able to feel or express emotions, does not mean that you do not have emotions.

author: listener
text: After such a traumatic event that you experienced, your central nervous system goes into defensive mode (dorsal vagal nerves) that protect you from any further harm.

author: listener
text: What this means is if you were to feel your emotions related to your rape, you would have a sense of being overwhelmed, possibly re-experiencing the traumatic event.
