author: speaker
text:
My therapist is gay so there are no sexual issues here. However, my therapist for six years has made me believe that he cares about me and that we are friends. I have loaned money to him many times, and he always paid me back.
   I had a medical emergency last weekend and I was heavily medicated. I knew that this therapist came into my home and wrote down my credit card information so he could pay back what he owed me, but this therapist dropped me off and never came again. I don't know what to do.

author: listener
text: Therapists, regardless of the discipline (i. e.  licensed professional counselor, social worker, psychologist) are expected to put the health and well-being of the client first.

author: listener
text: Each professional discipline does have a code of ethics as well as a licensing board in each state.

author: listener
text: In order to get licensed the therapist must agree to abide by the highest standards of conduct including state, local and federal regulations in addition to the code of conduct.

author: listener
text: You do have the option of reporting this person to the appropriate licencing board in your state.

author: speaker
text: I am an international student, and it is my first semester in graduate school in the United States. I faced a cultural shock, and I was so depressed when I arrived here. My counselor in the university was my savior. He helped me a great deal. Now I am going back to my country for a vacation. I was thinking to get him something special with my country's name on it, and I remembered that he likes wine. My country is known for that. Is it appropriate to give him wine as a gift after Christmas?

author: listener
text: This is a great question.

author: listener
text: In general it is not appropriate for counselors to accept gifts from their clients.

author: listener
text: There are some exceptions to this general rule - including a recognition that there may be a valid cultural aspect to this type of gift giving.

author: listener
text: It might be best to simply offer your counselor a holiday card as an expression of your feelings.

author: listener
text: You could also talk to your counselor about the gift and ask if him it if would be appropriate.

author: listener

author: listener
text: Hi, Different therapists are guided by the ethical guidelines of their own associations or colleges when it comes to receiving gifts, so this may differ a bit from therapist to therapist.

author: listener
text: It's important to me that I be sensitive to cultural norms, and to my client's needs.

author: listener
text: In Canada, and the US, it is customary for people to sometimes express gratitude with a small gift, and I have from time to time received small tokens of appreciation because I believe it would be rude to refuse this.

author: listener
text: It is never necessary to give a therapist a gift, but if you wish to express your gratitude in this way, I don't think it's inappropriate.

author: speaker
text: I need help knowing how to deal with stress. What can I do?

author: listener
text: Something different works for each of us.

author: listener
text: There are the outward answers of self-pampering and making your home and work environment as pleasant as possible.

author: listener
text: A deeper level way to decrease stress is through exercise or alternative practices like yoga or tai chi.

author: listener
text: If the stress is more deeply rooted than temporarily feeling irritated for a few days, then give yourself some time to reflect and clarify what the meaning of the stress is to you.

author: listener
text: Self-understanding and appreciating your efforts to know yourself may decrease stress because you'll be more focused and attentive to who you are.

author: listener
text: This will influence you overall to make good decisions for yourself and these will naturally be ones which decrease stress as much as possible.

author: listener
text: Those kinds of thoughts can be quite difficult to handle, but if they are your own thoughts (and not voices you are hearing, which can be very different), they likely are not new to you.

author: listener
text: From what I've learned from clients I work with, often these thoughts have been quite useful for them over the course of their lives, that through criticizing oneself, it is a way of motivating oneself.

author: listener
text: However, in your case and in most of those clients, it has caught up to them and it's almost like they no longer need the motivation (that they can do just fine motivating themselves by themselves!

author: listener
text: )I think it's important to see these thoughts as the voice of the "inner critic. "

author: listener
text: That inner critic was there for a long time, again, because "it" (I like to identify it as a thing inside of you) thought that you needed motivation in the form of criticism to stay on task with your life.

text: When we are too young to distinguish whether what a grown person tells us, feels accurate, we absorb their opinions as our own.

At this point i don't give a fuck about my life or what will happen. Just need a quick, silent, painless way to DIE.

author: listener
text: First of all go take a bath to be clean.

author: listener
text: Then go eat your favourite food cause its gonna be the last time right?

author: listener
text: Now i want you to go take a good amount of sleep and when you wake up do this: Start being passive about negative things.

author: listener
text: Life is too good and at the same time too bad to not experience it.

author: speaker
text: I've felt this way my whole life (25 years). My family lives a state over. It hasn't gotten better thus far, despite serious effort. I don't know why it would possibly get better now. I think I'm just not fit to be happy.

author: listener
text: It must be difficult being away from the rest of your family.

author: listener
text: I wish I could help you feel better about all this, it sounds like it has been challenging.

author: listener
text: If you don't mind my asking, what has been going on?

author: speaker
text: I don't like being me. I don't like my job. I don't like the way I act. I don't like the way I look. He hates that I hate myself which is making me hate myself more.

author: listener
text: I'm glad you're in good health, but I get that there doesn't have to be anything "wrong" to make it difficult to be happy.

author: listener
text: Not feeling satisfied with your job, your appearance, and your personality and feeling that you can't do anything about it is painful; It's difficult to find meaning when you feel powerless.

author: listener
text: I understand that feeling of powerlessness takes its toll, and I hope you'll feel better a bit further down the road.

author: speaker
text: Trigger warnings for sexual assault and self harm. Abandoned by friends and family, in pain, medical bills stacking up fast, when her Ex enters the picture. #Her host family:   Through all of this the host family she works for has become increasingly exploitative. Her host family is working her to death.

author: listener
text: I would pay particular attention to what [our tips post](URL says about not having to fix or change anything in order to make a supportive difference.

author: listener
text: Your friend has been through a tremendous amount, and it's natural to focus on her situation and experiences, but if you can shift the focus to her emotions (the tips go into quite a lot of detail about this), I think that's the best chance to reduce her risk of following through on her plan.

author: speaker
text: Thank you! I will give that a read and work on incorporating it into my communications with her. It just feels like for every step forward, we're going 2 steps back and I'm helpless to do anything about it.

author: listener
text: >  It just feels like for every step forward, we're going 2 steps back and I'm helpless to do anything about it.

author: speaker
text: I can't keep feeling like I do now. It would suck making my mum upset but if she knew how i was feeling she would understand.

author: listener
text: Hey, I'm glad you wrote out everything on your mind.

author: listener
text: The last 2 years have sounded rough, the help you have received so far is shocking, at least to me, how little they have done to help.

author: listener
text: Your lack of energy and drive seems to be your biggest concerns.

author: listener
text: It's great to express yourself like this as well, so others can listen and provide their thoughts.

author: speaker
text: thanks. My mum's talked about her struggles with depression around my age  but she said she tried therapy and a few different antidepressants, but the only thing that made things better was waiting it out. She never got this bad though, and I'm pretty worried that I'm not going to get better for years, especially if I can't get help.

author: listener
text: I realise that a lack of energy and spirit is leaving you feel hopeless, especially not being able to talk to anyone for 4 weeks.

author: listener
text: It's possible solutions that didn't work for her, may work for you and vice versa.

author: listener
text: You are getting help though and that's important.

author: listener
text: Have you considered possibly volunteering?

author: listener
text: It may sound silly as right now you require the support, but it might help you find something that makes you feel worthwhile.

author: speaker

author: listener

author: listener
text: In fact, most people who come to see me for counselling have more than one issue they would like to work on in psychotherapy and most times these are all interconnected.

author: listener
text: No job is worth your life, I know they are hard to come by in many situations... but not worth dying for

I'm working on telling myself things will be okay, but sometimes it just feels impossible. Thank you again for the advice, it means a lot. I think I just really needed to vent that to someone today.

author: listener

author: speaker
text: I have made multiple references to suicide and she has done nothing. Sure, I’ve been diagnosed with depression, gone to art therapy, even tried a horse club thing to make me happier, but NOTHING IS FUCKING WORKING. I’ve ripped my family apart and i’m pretty sure my mum is even more depressed because of me.

author: listener
text: You can’t be a total failure!

author: listener
text: What are some things you like to do, I’m sure there’s some or even a lot of things you’re good at.

author: speaker
text: You must have never met a total failure before if you think I can’t be one. Oh, well, nice to meet you.

author: listener
text: I have, and I know how I can prove you’re not a total failure.

author: listener
text: You see, a person calling themselves a total failure is paradoxical, as they succeeded in seeing that they have had these failures.

author: listener
text: A person who Is a total failure would not know they have failed at all as they would’ve failed to see it.

author: listener
text: See you’re not a total failure at all!

author: speaker
text: You genuinely expect me to believe that recognising that I am a failure and making an account for a social media website makes me not a failure?

author: listener
text: No, what I’m saying is that it is illogical for you to think you’re a total failure, you might’ve messed up a few times or even a lot maybe... but that doesn’t matter because everybody fails sometimes and we need to appreciate the small victories we get.

text: How does a counselor decide when to end counseling sessions or to terminate working with a client?

author: listener
text: Hi there, There are a number of reasons why a therapeutic relationship might end including, but not limited to the client reaching their goals, the client reaching a place of acceptance where they wish to remain or even a breach within the relationship.

author: listener
text: The last aspect should likely be taken to supervision in order to be fully processed.

author: listener
text: All of these things could happen, and usually happen organically (again, except for the last example).

author: listener
text: Your question, however, was about the counselor ending treatment.

author: speaker
text: I may have survived last night, but I’m barely hanging on by a thread now. I’m considering visiting a doctor very soon as I can’t cope any longer all by myself. They’ve left and it’s gone and now it’s back to the darkness in my mind...

text: I’m glad you’re going to get help.

author: listener
text: I’ve tried just letting the thoughts pass and think it’s just my OCD working against me and sometime that helps but other times it doesn’t.

author: listener
text: Again I’m happy you’re getting help and I hope you recover from the horrible disorder that is OCD.

text: This isn't about me but my brother in law who has struggled with suicidal thoughts since a child. Let me give some background info, my husband's family is very religious, homeschooled and his brother doesn't have a S/O or a good network of friends like my husband and their older sister. Last night, he expressed to their mom that he was having suicidal thoughts and her solution was to tell him that she would call the cops to stop him.

author: listener
text: Damn, that is a terrible way to respond when your own child confides in you.

author: listener
text: There can be a few reasons why you might feel this way.

author: listener
text: First, it is always unnerving to see a person who is a stranger and to share intimate things with that stranger.

author: listener
text: You mentioned it has only been a couple of sessions.

author: listener
text: Your anxiety might subside as you continue to see your therapist and grow more comfortable with him/her.

author: listener
text: Another reason why you might feel particularly nervous is perhaps you are not comfortable sharing things.

author: listener
text: As children, we might have bad experiences opening up to others.

author: listener
text: Someone might bully or ridicule us, and that experience can stay with us for a long time, making it extra scary to share our intimate feelings and thoughts with others.

author: listener
text: If this the case, as you continue with your sessions and have positive interactions with your therapists, this anxiety will subside with time and you will re-learn that it is safe to share.

author: listener
text: And the last thought why you might feel the shakes is perhaps you know that you need to talk about some past experiences or memories that are uncomfortable and difficult.

text: I start counseling/therapy in a few days (I'm freaking out) but my main fear is that I'll cry and embarrass myself, is it something to worry about?

author: listener
text: Hi there !

author: listener
text: As someone who has practiced as a clinical psychologist for 25 years , I would say that crying is NOTHING TO WORRY ABOUT AT ALL !

author: listener
text: Almost every single person I have worked with has cried at one point or another.

author: speaker
text: I start counseling/therapy in a few days (I'm freaking out) but my main fear is that I'll cry and embarrass myself, is it something to worry about?

author: listener
text: Hi there !

author: listener
text: As someone who has practiced as a clinical psychologist for 25 years , I would say that crying is NOTHING TO WORRY ABOUT AT ALL !

author: listener
text: Almost every single person I have worked with has cried at one point or another.

author: listener
text: Starting therapy takes a lot of courage; when you work with a therapist ,once you feel safe ,  you talk about a lot of very private and potentially emotional things that you may have never discussed with anyone before.

author: listener
text: I have seen  people cry with sadness , cry with relief at releasing painful things they have held onto for a long time, cry because they feel so relieved that they finally feel heard.

author: listener
text: I myself have sometimes cried with clients because some things they talk about are so profoundly moving.

author: listener
text: I can assure you that most , if not all , therapists expect clients to cry  and there is nothing to be embarrassed about.

author: listener
text: Crying can be very cathartic and can allow us to release a lot of painful feelings we have been stuffing down.

author: listener
text: Crying is  often a sign that you are really working things through and getting in touch with feelings that you need to get in touch with in order to heal .

author: listener
text: So , to summarize , don't worry at all about crying!

author: listener
text: It will probably feel uncomfortable  at first , but I promise you , you will not be judged for crying in therapy.

author: speaker
text: I start counseling/therapy in a few days (I'm freaking out) but my main fear is that I'll cry and embarrass myself, is it something to worry about?

author: listener
text: Please do not worry about crying.

author: listener
text: People cry, laugh, rage, rant, and talk during counseling sessions.

author: listener
text: Part of the therapy process is to look at your feelings, and to feel what you are actually feeling (instead of what you think you should feel).

author: listener
text: So if you need to cry, that's ok.

text: In the last two months I have had my left tube removed because of an ectopic pregnancy, lost 3 of my best friends, been hospitalised twice for being suicidal, and now my fiancé no longer wants me. I have never been at rock bottom like this. I feel so alone and have tried texting a few people to talk but they must be asleep. Or probably are sick of me leaning on them with my depression and issues. I just feel lost and helpless.

author: listener
text: Might have to get back to basics, looking after you so you can function, working to keep your job, realizing that you have worth and that if those other people don't want in, that's their loss.

author: speaker
text: I was planning on hanging myself this week, but I'm having second thoughts. I've never been happy, and whenever I plan to kill myself, I never go though with it. I don't know why. It's not like my depression will go away. I guess I just keep hoping that I'll find a reason to keep going. I know that in either a few weeks or months I'll be planning suicide again. It's an endless cycle.

author: listener
text: Depression doesn't go away but it is possible to get better at managing it over time.
